I removed the live-coding round from my interview loop fourteen months ago. I have hired eleven engineers since. Not one of them has shipped worse code than the engineers I hired the old way.

## What we replaced it with

A two-hour collaborative working session on a real, scoped problem from our backlog. Candidates use whatever tools they actually use day-to-day: Cursor, Copilot, ChatGPT, their own mother. We pay them for their time.

## What we're now actually selecting for

Three things, in order of weight:

- Taste: the ability to look at three plausible solutions and explain why one is correct for this codebase.
- Decomposition: turning a vague product ask into a sequence of changes a teammate could review.
- Communication under uncertainty: saying 'I don't know yet' followed by a credible plan to find out.

Notice what's not on that list. Memorizing language trivia. Reversing a binary tree on a whiteboard. Being able to outpace an LLM at typing.

## The objection I hear most

"But how do you know they can actually code?" You watch them code. For two hours. On a real problem. With their real tools. The signal is enormous.
